lomew, Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"英国藍卡爾哈伍德","Harwood, Lancashire, England":"英国英格兰藍卡爾哈伍德","lifeSummary":"Lady Eline Dean是Richard Deane的女儿，于大约1548年出生在英国英格兰藍卡爾哈伍德。她于1577年7月20日与Gyles Henrie Aimsworth在英国藍卡爾哈伍德结婚。他们至少是3个儿子的父母。她于1563年住在英国英格兰爾布雷雷頓。她去世于1603年享年56岁。"},"hr":{"Abt 1548–1603":"oko 1548.–1603.","1548–1603":"1548–1603.","1547–1600":"1547–1600","1567–1615":"1567.–1615","1567–Male":"1567.–preminuo","1580–Male":"1580–preminuo","–Male":"preminuo","1547":"1547","about 1580":"oko 1580.","1567":"1567.","1600":"1600","20 Jul 1577":"20. srpnja 1577.","08 Dec 1563":"8. prosinca 1563.","23 October 1600":"23. listopada 1600.","1580":"1580","Abt 1548":"oko 1548.","1615":"1615","1603":"1603.","1548":"1548","Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, Engleska, United Kingdom","Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Bolton, Lancashire, Engleska, United Kingdom",", Brereton-cum-Smethwick, Cheshire, England":"Brereton, Cheshire, Engleska, United Kingdom","St Bartholomew, Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"Abt 1548–1603":"okolo 1548–1603","1548–1603":"1548–1603","1547–1600":"1547–1600","1567–1615":"1567–1615","1567–Male":"1567–Zesnulý","1580–Male":"1580–Zesnulý","–Male":"Zesnulý","1547":"1547","about 1580":"okolo 1580","1567":"1567","1600":"1600","20 Jul 1577":"20. července 1577","08 Dec 1563":"8. prosince 1563","23 October 1600":"23. října 1600","1580":"1580","Abt 1548":"okolo 1548","1615":"1615","1603":"1603","1548":"1548","Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Bolton, Lancashire, Anglie, United Kingdom",", Brereton-cum-Smethwick, Cheshire, England":"Brereton, Cheshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","St Bartholomew, Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, Anglie","Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"Abt 1548–1603":"omkring 1548–1603","1548–1603":"1548–1603","1547–1600":"1547–1600","1567–1615":"1567–1615","1567–Male":"1567–Afdød","1580–Male":"1580–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1547":"1547","about 1580":"omkring 1580","1567":"1567","1600":"1600","20 Jul 1577":"20. juli 1577","08 Dec 1563":"8. december 1563","23 October 1600":"23. oktober 1600","1580":"1580","Abt 1548":"omkring 1548","1615":"1615","1603":"1603","1548":"1548","Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom",", Brereton-cum-Smethwick, Cheshire, England":"Brereton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","St Bartholomew, Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1548–1603":"circa 1548–1603","1548–1603":"1548–1603","1547–1600":"1547–1600","1567–1615":"1567–1615","1567–Male":"1567–Overleden","1580–Male":"1580–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1547":"1547","about 1580":"circa 1580","1567":"1567","1600":"1600","20 Jul 1577":"20 juli 1577","08 Dec 1563":"8 december 1563","23 October 1600":"23 oktober 1600","1580":"1580","Abt 1548":"circa 1548","1615":"1615","1603":"1603","1548":"1548","Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Bolton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk",", Brereton-cum-Smethwick, Cheshire, England":"Brereton, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","St Bartholomew, Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1548–1603":"about 1548–1603","1548–1603":"1548–1603","1547–1600":"1547–1600","1567–1615":"1567–1615","1567–Male":"1567–Deceased","1580–Male":"1580–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1547":"1547","about 1580":"about 1580","1567":"1567","1600":"1600","20 Jul 1577":"20 July 1577","08 Dec 1563":"8 December 1563","23 October 1600":"23 October 1600","1580":"1580","Abt 1548":"about 1548","1615":"1615","1603":"1603","1548":"1548","Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom",", Brereton-cum-Smethwick, Cheshire, England":"Brereton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","St Bartholomew, Great Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dean","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>dene</i> ‘valley’ (Old English <i>denu</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places in various parts of England named Dean or Dene from this word.","English: nickname or occupational name for the servant of a dean or nickname for someone thought to resemble a dean. A dean was an ecclesiastical official, the head of a chapter of canons or a church official with jurisdiction over a sub-division of an archdeaconry. Though no doubt some deans had illegitimate children, they were officially celibate, and in the main the surname is probably a nickname in origin, similar to   Bishop  ,   Prior  ,   Priest  , and   Monk  . The Middle English word <i>deen</i>, <i>dien</i>, <i>dein</i>, is a borrowing of Old French <i>d(e)ien</i>, <i>doien</i> from Latin <i>decanus</i> (originally a leader of ten men, from <i>decem</i> ‘ten’), and thus is a cognate of   Deacon  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Deyne</i> (or <i>Dene</i>) a rhyming pet form of <i>Reynald</i> (see   Reginald  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Bishop","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>bissop</i>, <i>biscop</i>, Old English <i>bisc(e)op</i> ‘bishop’, which comes via Latin from Greek <i>episkopos</i> ‘overseer’. The Greek word was adopted early in the Christian era as a title for an overseer of a local community of Christians, and has yielded cognates in every European language: French <i>évêque</i>, Italian <i>vescovo</i>, Spanish <i>obispo</i>, Russian <i>yepiskop</i>, German <i>Bischof</i>, etc. The word came to be applied as a surname for a variety of reasons, among them a supposed resemblance in bearing or appearance to a bishop, and selection as the ‘boy bishop’ on Saint Nicholas's Feast Day. In some instances the surname is from the rare Middle English (Old English) personal name <i>Biscop</i> ‘bishop’. As an Irish surname it is adopted for <b>Mac Giolla Easpaig</b>, meaning ‘servant of the bishop’ (see   Gillespie  ). In North America, this surname has absorbed, by assimilation and translation, at least some of continental European cognates, e.g. German   Bischoff  , Polish, Rusyn, Czech, and Slovak   Biskup  , Slovenian <b>Škof</b> (see   Skoff  )."]},{"name":"Denman","meanings":["English: topographic name denoting a ‘dweller in the valley’ from Middle English <i>dene</i> + <i>man</i> (see   Dean   1)."]},{"name":"Deans","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Dean  ."]},{"name":"Denson","meanings":["patronymic meaning ‘son of the dean’, see   Dean   2. Since medieval deans were celibate, their sons would have to have been illegitimate, but <i>le Dene</i> was probably also used as a non-clerical nickname, so illegitimacy is not necessarily to be inferred.","patronymic meaning ‘son of <i>Deyne</i> or <i>Dene</i>’, a pet form of <i>Reynald</i> (Reginald); see   Dean   3.","English:"]},{"name":"Deen","meanings":["English: variant of   Dean  .","Dutch: ethnic name for a Dane, Middle Dutch <i>Deen</i>. Alternatively, from the personal name <i>Deen</i>, based on Old High German <i>degan</i> ‘squire, nobleman, thane’."]},{"name":"Denton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places so called. The vast majority, including those in Cambridgeshire, Cumbria, Dumfries, Durham, Kent, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, Northumberland, Oxfordshire, Sussex, and Yorkshire are named from Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’ (see   Dean   1) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. An isolated example in Northamptonshire appears in the Domesday Book as <i>Dodintone</i> meaning ‘enclosure, settlement associated with <i>Dodda</i> or <i>Dudda</i>’."]},{"name":"Dann","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>dene</i> ‘valley’ (Old English <i>denu</i>), which is often found as <i>dane</i> in placenames in Essex, Hertfordshire, Bedfordshire, Kent, and Sussex. Compare   Dean  .","English: perhaps from a pet form of the Middle English personal name   Daniel  .","German: topographic name for someone who lived by a pine tree, from Old High German <i>tanna</i> ‘pine tree’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine)."]},{"name":"Deaner","meanings":["English (Worcestershire): topographic name for someone who lived in a valley, from Middle English <i>dene</i> ‘(thickly wooded) valley’ (see   Dean   1) + the suffix <i>-er</i>, denoting an inhabitant.","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Diener  ."]}]},{"name":"Eline","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally an Old French form of   Helen  , but now generally regarded as an independent name. The Greek and Latin forms of the name had a long vowel in the second syllable, which produced this form (as opposed to   Ellen  ) in Old French. In Arthurian legend,  Elaine  is the name of one of the women who fell in love with  Lancelot . The name occurs in this form in the 15th-century English Morte d'Arthur of  Thomas Malory . In the 19th century it was popularized in one of  Tennyson's  Idylls of the King (  1859 ). Most of the characters in Arthurian legend have names that are Celtic in origin, although subjected to heavy French influence, and it has therefore been suggested that <i>Elaine</i> may actually be derived from a Welsh word meaning ‘hind’ or ‘fawn’."],"variants":[{"name":"Elain","meanings":["Originally an Old French form of   Helen  , but now generally regarded as an independent name. The Greek and Latin forms of the name had a long vowel in the second syllable, which produced this form (as opposed to   Ellen  ) in Old French. In Arthurian legend,  Elaine  is the name of one of the women who fell in love with  Lancelot . The name occurs in this form in the 15th-century English Morte d'Arthur of  Thomas Malory . In the 19th century it was popularized in one of  Tennyson's  Idylls of the King (  1859 ). Most of the characters in Arthurian legend have names that are Celtic in origin, although subjected to heavy French influence, and it has therefore been suggested that <i>Elaine</i> may actually be derived from a Welsh word meaning ‘hind’ or ‘fawn’."]},{"name":"Elayne","meanings":["Originally an Old French form of   Helen  , but now generally regarded as an independent name. The Greek and Latin forms of the name had a long vowel in the second syllable, which produced this form (as opposed to   Ellen  ) in Old French. In Arthurian legend,  Elaine  is the name of one of the women who fell in love with  Lancelot . The name occurs in this form in the 15th-century English Morte d'Arthur of  Thomas Malory . In the 19th century it was popularized in one of  Tennyson's  Idylls of the King (  1859 ). Most of the characters in Arthurian legend have names that are Celtic in origin, although subjected to heavy French influence, and it has therefore been suggested that <i>Elaine</i> may actually be derived from a Welsh word meaning ‘hind’ or ‘fawn’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Eline Dean was born about 1548, in Harwood, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Richard Deane. She married Gyles Henrie Aimsworth on 20 July 1577, in Harwood, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She lived in Brereton, Cheshi